## Look ahead any where in the string
^(?=.*[a-z])(?=.*[A-Z])(?=.*\d)(?=.*[\W_]).{8,}$
^ → Start of string
(?=.*[a-z]) → At least one lowercase
(?=.*[A-Z]) → At least one uppercase
(?=.*\d) → At least one digit
(?=.*[\W_]) → At least one special character
.{8,} → Minimum 8 characters
$ → End of string

## Negative Look Ahead
(?!pattern)
\d(?!px)  ###Matches digits not followed by px

#Look Behind
(?<=pattern)
(?<=\$)\d+
Matches 100 because $ is behind it

(?<=\$)\d+(?:\.\d{2})?
Matches
$19.99
$100

#Negative Look Behind
(?<!pattern)
(?<!\$)\d+
Matches numbers not preceded by $

Example:
$100USD
(?<=\$)\d+(?=USD)
Matches 100 because $ is behind & USD ahead

#Capturing/Non Capturing group
(cat|dog)      # capturing group to be used later as \1 \2 etc
(?:cat|dog)s?  # Non Capturing Group matches Matches cat, cats, dog, dogs  ## ? at then end means 0 or 1 ## ?: avoid creating unnecessary groups

\1 — Backreference inside the regex pattern
(\w+)\s\1 -- Matchhes repeated words
$1 used in replacement 
Regex.Replace("Doe, John", @"(\w+), (\w+)", "$2 $1")


## Conditional matching
123-456-7890 
4567890
^(?:(\d{3})-)?(?(1)\d{3}-\d{4}|\d{7})$
123 stored in 1
^(?:(\d{3})-)? matches 123 0 or 1 times
If 123 exists matches 456-7890, if 123 does not ext matched 4567890
123-4567890 -fails, 1234567890 fails

